'''Tsukinami no Matsuri''' is one of the {{ill|Shinto|8=en}} {{ill|Festival|festivals|8=en}} . At {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|Ise Shrine|8=en}}, the three festivals held in {{ill|June|8=en}} and {{ill|December|8=en}} and the {{ill|10=ja|11=神嘗祭|Kannamesai Festival|8=en}} are called the Sansetsu Festival and Sanjisai Festival.

== history ==
It seems that in the past it was held every month, but {{ill|Engishiki|the Engishiki|8=en}} stipulates that it should be held on the 11th of June and December, and it was held at {{ill|10=ja|11=朝廷_(日本)|Imperial Court in Kyoto|lt=the Imperial Court|8=en}} and at Ise Shrine.

On the morning of the 11th day, {{ill|Department of Divinities|the Shinto priests|8=en}} at the Imperial Court distributed {{ill|10=ja|11=幣帛|hanpei|lt=offerings|8=en}} (hanpei) to the 304 {{ill|10=ja|11=祝_(神職)|Deity|lt=deities|8=en}} of {{ill|Kansai region|the Kinai region|8=en}} <ref name="yougo">{{Cite book|title=日本史B用語集―A併記|last=全国歴史教育研究協議会|publisher={{ill|山川出版社|8=en}}|isbn=9784634013025|edition=改訂版|series=|author-link=|access-date=|和書}}</ref> . In the evening, a ceremony called "jinkonjiki" was held at the Shinkaden Hall of {{ill|10=ja|11=中和院|Chukain Temple|8=en}}, in which the emperor and the gods ate grains from the previous year (old grains) <ref name="yougo" /> .

After that, handicraft offerings were only practiced at Ise Shrine, and during {{ill|Muromachi period|the Muromachi period,|8=en}} handicraft offerings were abolished due to events such as {{ill|Ōnin War|the Onin War|8=en}}, but were revived after {{ill|Meiji period|the Meiji period|8=en}} . Currently, many shrines across the country hold monthly festivals on specific days each month.


*

